Change log:
0.1.0 (31-03-2026):

I have added a simple file handling system and the main function.
The main function could open text files and read them, or open text files and write to them.
At this stage the program was purely procedural and had no encryption functionality.

The file handler class was introduced shortly after this initial version.
The file handler class contains two functions:

Read, which opens a file based on the file path on the computer and reads its contents.
Write, which opens a file and writes data to it.

This change marked the first step toward structuring the program using classes instead of only functions.

0.1.1 (04-04-2026):

Added substitution cipher functionality.
This introduced the first encryption method in the program.

The substitution cipher works by rearranging the alphabet based on a key provided by the user.
Each letter in the plaintext is replaced with a corresponding letter in a shifted or reordered alphabet.

At this stage, the cipher was still separate from the file handling system and was tested independently before integration.

0.1.2 (10-04-2026):

Integrated the substitution cipher into the file handling system.
The program could now read a text file, encrypt its contents using the substitution cipher, and write the result to a new file.

This was the first version where file handling and encryption worked together as a single system.

0.1.3 (18-04-2026):

Added Polybius cipher using a 5x5 grid system.
This introduced a second encryption method alongside the substitution cipher.

The Polybius cipher converts letters into coordinate pairs based on their position in a 5x5 grid.
The letter J is merged with I to fit the grid structure.

At this stage, the program supported multiple encryption methods but they were still separate and not combined.

1.0.0 (22-04-2026):

Introduced the Cipher Engine system.
This allowed multiple cipher methods to be executed in a defined order.

The system now supported:

Substitution cipher
Polybius cipher
Sequential execution of both (Substitution → Polybius)

This marked the first version of a structured encryption pipeline.

1.1.0 (25-04-2026):

Added Tkinter graphical user interface.
The program could now be used through a visual interface instead of only the command line.

The UI included:

File selection system
Codeword input field
Encode and Decode buttons
Output display box

This improved usability significantly and made the program more interactive.

Attempted 6×6 Polybius Expansion:

A 6×6 version of the Polybius cipher was also tested to expand the character set to include numbers as well as letters. However, this caused compatibility issues with the substitution cipher, which only supports A–Z. The mismatch led to inconsistent encoding and decoding in the chained system.

As a result, the 6×6 version was removed and the system was reverted back to the standard 5×5 Polybius cipher (with J merged into I) to restore full compatibility and reversibility.

1.1.0 (27-04-2026):

Refined the cipher system and fixed compatibility issues between Substitution and Polybius ciphers.

The Polybius cipher was reverted to a 5x5 grid system to ensure compatibility with the substitution cipher.
This removed issues caused by expanded character sets and ensured consistent encoding and decoding.

The system now works as a stable chained encryption model:
Substitution → Polybius → Reverse decoding process.
